segments.text: Were you representing an institution, a spirit, or anything as you were marching down the street?
Now, of the four places,
Which one did you enjoy most, the four core trip?
Now, you marched down Main Street in Houston, Congress in Austin, and in Dallas, was it Elm or Main?
Or do you remember?
I'm assuming it was.
I think it was commerce.
Oh, really?
Oh, okay.
Didn't commerce one way that way?
It's a bigger group.
Well, it parallels.
Yeah, it parallels the other two.
Okay.
I hadn't thought about that.
Commerce.
And all three were busy.
I think that's commerce, yeah.
I'm pretty sure.
Yeah, Baker.
I think the Baker was on that side and the office on this side.
I hadn't thought of that.
I apologize.
Thank you.
Do you have any special football game memories?
I don't know.
I'm not sure.
I don't know.
I don't know.
I don't know.
Where was that day?
And what did you freshmen do to celebrate?
I remember like one, we had won one last year.
We won one game.
And we beat Georgia.
That's the only game we won.
Okay, we're getting now near the end of the serious ones.
Final review and what did that, what were, what was it, where was it, what did it mean to you emotionally?
Final review.
I know you might want to review the previous year.
The year that you go around the first time you've seen it, and the next time you go in and see it.
That's actually the greatest thing you want to do.
Also, the other thing I would say is take a look at the program.
So, I really just can't watch them.
I can't watch them.
What did you get for the boots?
Were the boots new to you or had you bought them?
As you're preparing to leave the campus, what kind of a world did you think you were going into?
Whatever it was, I thought I could come.
I thought I was a failure.
I thought I was a problem.
That's what pulled me in.
The whole world.
No.
I had no question.
Did you already have a job by commissary?
Yes, I did.
With Michael and the children.
I had $416 million.
I knew it was going to be for children.
How did, what role did A&M play in helping you make those contacts?
Oh, let me tell you, I didn't have to.
I hardly had to interview.
At that point, they were so pleased with me.
I know it was just almost.
I didn't hire any graduates.
That's not true of many other students.
Look from the back there.
But I know many other people that had so many friends in one of the tribes that didn't matter.
But it was almost, and I had worked for them a summer prior to that.
I think I mentioned that I had to be part of the patrolling community curriculum.
I have to have one.
How'd you feel when you got that Aggie ring?
Oh yeah, no, but I mean when that time?
No way.
I wear it off campus, you know, at home.
Yeah, OK.
But it takes 100 and something hours, because I had that.
Most of the engineering students had it at the, I think I had it at the end of my junior year.
I can't think of it.
Was there any kind of a ritual that you and your buddies did when you first bought the ring?
Did you put it in any kind of a liquid?
Oh, well, soul dressing.
Huh?
Soul dressing.
Soul dressing.
What, the soul dressing?
You put on the soul dressing.
You put, you whacking it in with the soul dressing.
You take a flesh cloth and you wipe it off.
But you didn't put it in a pitcher of alcoholic beverage?
No, no, I didn't.
It wasn't that strong.
Because I've heard that some did.
Oh, I can believe that.
And I've heard that a few even got it in their mouth and almost swallowed it.
Oh, my God.
What has it meant to wear that ring?
I think you know the answer before I say it.
I've never gone anywhere without it.
I certainly wouldn't go anywhere.
See, there are only a few schools today that pay any attention to rings.
The few Ivy Leagues, the academies, and then a few other separate land grants.
Clemson, I think maybe Auburn, but that's about it.
And senior rings are pretty well gone almost everywhere else.
Aggieland is one of a few.
yearbook still going.
One of my friends up in Missouri, a fellow named Don, oh yeah, a fellow named Don Walsworth, he's the owner of an old family printing operation in a teeny little town named Marceline.
And a couple years ago I ran into him, I said, hey Don, how's business going?
He said, I just got a contract for the biggest yearbook
in America going to print it.
And I said, well, how'd you get the A&M contract?
He said, how would you know?
I said, well, it's just a random guess when you said the biggest.
Just a random guess.
And he was saying, oh, he said, not only is it big in thickness, he said it's big in number of copies.
And I said, well, they're so square and so old fashioned, they believe that having a yearbook still is good.
OK, now we're to the real hot.
What are the contributing factors that make up Aggie spirit?
Where does it come from?
Where does it come from?
All of what I'm saying is that you have to explain it to someone.
And you have to guess whether or not you have it coming on them.
And there's problems under there.
I probably ought to go a little bit different.
And I guess when you see, as you mentioned, something like Ed Davis and Clayton Williams, what I think about that experience is that you go in to Clayton Williams and get $2 million.
He thinks just over and over.
He breaks out in tears.
All right, were there some events when you were a student that are part of that?
Let's hear it.
Well, I think, there again, I think, I think, uh, I think some of the towns, uh, uh, muster the student songs, uh, which are always absolutely marvellous.
Oh, okay.
I spoke for about five minutes or so at a muster that we had in France this year.
I know you tripped an ollie, but it was pretty cool.
And before it was over, we had a gal there that was helping with the group.
She was married to a Frenchman who was living in France.
She was a tear.
And it's...
It's a pretty solid thing.
And then we ended up, we called out the names of several people very close to the association like Bud Meyers and Juanita.
They've been the traitor for years and I think maybe one of them.
I don't know if I really answered your question.
I don't think I did.
All right.
But it's one that you can't completely answer.
And you're going to be looking for an answer for it for always.
All right.
The last question.
What feelings do you hold in your heart for a man?
Let's see.
I wouldn't be where I am today without it.
Have it gone somewhere else.
I think the education, the leadership.
Mr. Berry?
The fact that you can still go back on campus and it really hasn't changed that much, even though it's huge.
I think the main thing that we want to do is try to keep it so that we still have the same feeling.
And so it's...
underprivileged people will still be able to go there and get the same kind of education.
It doesn't really matter what the race is.
so much that it gives you.
And it just keeps on giving.
It's hard to really repay it or give back enough.
You want to quit with that?
That's a great ending.
And I thank you, thank you, thank you.
